# Y · Modelfile for the fine-tuned edge tutor (Gemma 4 E4B + ControlSketch LoRA)
#
# Build the GGUF artefact first via the Unsloth Kaggle notebook
# (`training/unsloth_train.ipynb` step 8), drop it next to this file, then run:
#
#     ollama create y-gemma4 -f models/Modelfile.y-gemma4
#
# After this, the API will be able to serve the fine-tuned tutor by setting
# `model_choice=edge-ft` on the /lesson endpoint (or selecting "Edge
# fine-tuned (E4B+LoRA)" in the toolbar).
#
# If the GGUF export from the Unsloth notebook fails on your machine, swap
# the FROM line to `FROM gemma4:e4b` to keep the demo functional on the
# *base* Gemma 4 E4B and ship the LoRA on HF as a separate Unsloth-track
# artefact (judges can merge it locally).

FROM ./y-gemma4-svg-q4_k_m.gguf

# Decoding settings recommended for the Gemma 4 family (Unsloth + Google
# launch post). Gemma 4 supports the same sampling envelope as Gemma 3.
PARAMETER temperature 0.4
PARAMETER top_k 64
PARAMETER top_p 0.95
PARAMETER min_p 0.0
PARAMETER repeat_penalty 1.0
PARAMETER num_ctx 4096
PARAMETER num_predict 2048

TEMPLATE """{{ if .System }}<start_of_turn>user
{{ .System }}{{ end }}{{ if .Prompt }}
{{ .Prompt }}{{ end }}<end_of_turn>
<start_of_turn>model
{{ .Response }}<end_of_turn>
"""

# Bake in a thin system message so even a bare `ollama run y-gemma4` echos
# the project's whiteboard-tutor identity. The full system prompt (with the
# 9-tool registry and exemplars) is injected by api/teacher.py at request
# time, so this is just the elevator pitch -- keeps prompt budget free for
# the actual tools and few-shots.
SYSTEM """You are Y, a multi-tool whiteboard tutor. You teach by writing on the same board the student is using, exactly the way a human teacher does. Use the 9 tools (title, text, equation, box, node, arrow, line, draw, draw_part) defined by the host application's system prompt. Prefer [draw_part] blocks for any diagram whose shape matters; decompose into 2-5 named pedagogical parts."""
